 :tx/provenance :observed
 :tx/rationale "Create task: ONTOLOGY-DISCOVER-1: Ontological surprise detection — the daemon watches for unknown unknowns. FEGH detects missing BRIDGES between known clusters (known unknowns). This detects missing CATEGORIES entirely (unknown unknowns). APPROACH: (1) Topic clustering on :exploration/body text across recent sessions (TF-IDF or simple keyword frequency). (2) Map each cluster to nearest schema namespace via keyword overlap. (3) Clusters with no nearby namespace (similarity < threshold) = ontological surprise. (4) Surface as guidance: 'NEW CATEGORY: agents discuss performance/latency/caching but store has no :runtime/* attributes. Propose schema extension?' (5) Track proposed categories in W-alpha with the 6 lifecycle attributes. Categories that recur across 3+ sessions get promoted to formal schema proposal. Categories that appear once decay. FORMAL: Let S = attr namespaces in schema, O = concept clusters in observation stream. Ontological gap = O minus S. This is OBSERVER-6 (ontology discovery) connected to the daemon's introspective capability. FREE ENERGY: Standard F measures KL divergence within existing dimensions. Ontological surprise measures the DIMENSIONALITY GAP — states in P(reality) with no representation in Q(model). This is the system discovering its own blind spots by watching what users care about. VALIDATION: Would have auto-generated SCHEMA-RUNTIME-1 (runtime attributes were an unknown unknown until we hit the performance wall). ACCEPTANCE: (A) After 5+ sessions discussing a novel topic, daemon surfaces 'new category' suggestion. (B) Suggestion includes proposed namespace and example attributes. (C) False positive rate < 20 percent (most suggestions are genuinely novel). (D) Accepted categories auto-generate schema extension datoms. DEPENDS-ON: PERF-4 (daemon), BLANKET-DYNAMICS-1 (observation stream access). TRACES: ADR-FOUNDATION-032, ADR-FOUNDATION-031, OBSERVER-6, C7. FILE: crates/braid/src/daemon.rs + crates/braid-kernel/src/schema.rs"
